= Background

== Introduction

The background chapter (sometimes titled "Literature Review" or "Related Work") is an essential component of any doctoral thesis. A comprehensive review of the literature will provide background to the research, situate the work within the broader field, and identify gaps in the existing knowledge that the thesis aims to address. It should demonstrate a deep and critical engagement with the relevant literature.

At PhD level, this chapter is expected to provide a thorough and critical synthesis of the state of the art. It should not simply summarise existing work, but identify themes, contradictions, and open questions across the literature. The review should clearly establish the theoretical and empirical foundations upon which your experimental chapters build.

It may be helpful to break up this chapter into thematic sections, with each focused on a different area relevant to your research. For example, you might cover the core domain, related methodologies, theoretical frameworks, and adjacent fields.

